# ============================================================================
# PACKAGE EXPLANATIONS
# ============================================================================

# opencv-python:
# - Captures video from webcam
# - Displays video frames
# - Draws overlays and text
# - Basic image processing

# mediapipe:
# - Google's ML solution for pose estimation
# - Detects 33 body landmarks in real-time
# - Works on CPU (no GPU required)
# - Pre-trained models included
# - This is the CORE of fall detection

# numpy:
# - Mathematical operations
# - Array/matrix calculations
# - Used for coordinate transformations
# - Essential for angle calculations

# ============================================================================
# MEDIAPIPE POSE LANDMARKS
# ============================================================================

# MediaPipe detects these 33 body points:
# 
# Face (0-10):
# 0  - Nose
# 1  - Left Eye Inner
# 2  - Left Eye
# 3  - Left Eye Outer
# 4  - Right Eye Inner
# 5  - Right Eye
# 6  - Right Eye Outer
# 7  - Left Ear
# 8  - Right Ear
# 9  - Mouth Left
# 10 - Mouth Right
#
# Upper Body (11-16):
# 11 - Left Shoulder
# 12 - Right Shoulder
# 13 - Left Elbow
# 14 - Right Elbow
# 15 - Left Wrist
# 16 - Right Wrist
#
# Torso (17-22):
# 17 - Left Pinky
# 18 - Right Pinky
# 19 - Left Index
# 20 - Right Index
# 21 - Left Thumb
# 22 - Right Thumb
#
# Lower Body (23-32):
# 23 - Left Hip
# 24 - Right Hip
# 25 - Left Knee
# 26 - Right Knee
# 27 - Left Ankle
# 28 - Right Ankle
# 29 - Left Heel
# 30 - Right Heel
# 31 - Left Foot Index
# 32 - Right Foot Index

# ============================================================================
# INSTALLATION
# ============================================================================

# RECOMMENDED METHOD:
# 1. Create a virtual environment (optional but recommended):
#    python -m venv venv
#    
#    Activate it:
#    Windows: venv\Scripts\activate
#    Mac/Linux: source venv/bin/activate
#
# 2. Install all packages:
#    pip install -r requirements.txt

# ALTERNATIVE (Individual Installation):
# pip install opencv-python
# pip install mediapipe
# pip install numpy

# ============================================================================
# PLATFORM-SPECIFIC NOTES
# ============================================================================

# WINDOWS:
# - Should work out of the box
# - Audio alerts use winsound (built-in)

# macOS:
# - May need: pip install --upgrade pip
# - Audio uses 'say' command (built-in)
# - If camera issues: Check System Preferences > Security & Privacy

# LINUX:
# - May need additional packages:
#   sudo apt-get install python3-opencv
#   sudo apt-get install libgl1-mesa-glx  # For OpenCV display
#
# - For audio (optional):
#   sudo apt-get install espeak

# ============================================================================
# TROUBLESHOOTING
# ============================================================================

# "No module named 'cv2'":
# → pip install opencv-python

# "No module named 'mediapipe'":
# → pip install mediapipe

# "ImportError: libGL.so.1" (Linux):
# → sudo apt-get install libgl1-mesa-glx

# MediaPipe installation fails:
# → Try: pip install --upgrade pip
# → Then: pip install mediapipe

# Camera not working:
# → Check if another app is using it
# → Try different camera index (0, 1, 2)

# Slow performance:
# → Reduce camera resolution in script
# → Close other applications
# → Use model_complexity=0 for faster processing

